{{Infobox university |name = Australian National Academy of Music |native_name = |latin_name = |image = |motto = |established = 1994 |type = |endowment = |staff = 15 |faculty = 14 |president = |rector = |chancellor = |vice_chancellor = |head_label = |head = |students = 52 |undergrad = |postgrad = |doctoral = |city = [[Melbourne]] |state = Victoria |country = Australia |coor = {{coord|-37.8343|144.9598|type:edu_region:AU|display=inline,title}} |campus = [[South Melbourne Town Hall]] |free_label = |free = |colors = |colours = |mascot = |affiliations = [[University of Melbourne]] |website = http://www.anam.com.au/ }}
The '''Australian National Academy of Music''' (ANAM) is a classical music performance training facility. ANAM is a national organisation with students from across Australia and New Zealand. Located in [[South Melbourne, Victoria]], it is a member of the Australian Roundtable for Arts Training Excellence.<ref>{{Cite web |author=((Department of the Environment, Water, Heritage and the Arts)) |title=Arts training bodies |accessdate=3 October 2008 |date=15 September 2008 |url=http://www.arts.gov.au/arts_training_bodies |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080821130632/http://www.arts.gov.au/arts_training_bodies |archivedate=21 August 2008 |deadurl=yes }}</ref> Current Artistic Director Nick Deutsch was appointed in 2016 and past Artistic Directors include composer [[Brett Dean]] and clarinettist [[Paul Dean (clarinetist)|Paul Dean]] <ref>[http://www.australianstage.com.au/201003263321/news/melbourne/anam-announces-new-artistic-director.html "ANAM Announces New Artistic Director"] at Australian Stage, 26 March 2010</ref>
Established in 1994, ANAM's Professional Performance Program is flexible for students wishing to study their instrument in the following categories - strings, woodwind, brass, percussion, harp and keyboard instruments. From 2012, ANAM offers a master's degree delivered in collaboration with [[Queensland Conservatorium Griffith University]], along with Fellowship and short course opportunities.
==2008/09 funding crisis== On 23 October 2008, the [[Minister for the Environment, Heritage and the Arts (Australia)|Minister for the Arts]], [[Peter Garrett]], announced that ANAM would not receive any government funding in 2009<ref name=Age>[http://www.theage.com.au/national/canberra-axes-music-academy-funds-20081023-57gq.html Canberra axes music academy funds], Robin Usher, ''[[The Age]]'', 24 October 2008</ref> despite funding having been arranged initially in 1994 by the then [[Prime Minister of Australia|Prime Minister]], [[Paul Keating]]. A spokesman for Garret is reported to have said, "ANAM no longer represents the most efficient way of delivering support for elite classical music training." The ANAM Artistic Director Brett Dean said, "That is heart-breaking for music education in this country."
